{"title":"Scene-Intuitive Agent for Remote Embodied Visual Grounding","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"In remote embodied visual grounding (REVERIE), an agent must follow high-level instructions to both navigate to the correct location (where to stop) and localize the target object (what to attend to). Existing approaches struggle to infer scene-level intent from sparse language and to robustly ground objects across multi-view panoramas.","method":"Pretrain two complementary cross-modal grounding tasks with ViLBERT to inject where/what priors before learning a navigation policy. (1) Scene Grounding: formulate viewpoint–instruction alignment as a 5-way multiple-choice task using 36-view panoramas with ResNet features; compute alignment scores from ViLBERT’s CLS/IMG tokens and optimize a cross-entropy loss to identify the target viewpoint (e.g., 85.67%/66.43% accuracy on Val Seen/Unseen). (2) Object Grounding: a two-stage scheme—first fine-tune on single-image grounding, then further fine-tune on viewpoint-level grounding (aggregating all boxes across views) to capture cross-image object relations; this ViLPointer significantly outperforms prior pointers (e.g., MattNet) at the ground-truth viewpoint (73.26% vs 68.45 on Val Seen; 67.45% vs 56.63 on Val Unseen)."},{"problem":"Generating reliable navigation actions under high-level instructions requires integrating scene-level and object-level evidence over time, but standard recurrent policies have limited long-horizon memory and weak guidance from underspecified language.","method":"Use a memory-augmented attentive action decoder that treats the pretrained grounding models as encoders and fuses them with an addressable scene memory. The decoder: (a) conditions the instruction on the current panorama via ViLEncoder (ViLBERT+BiLSTM) to produce grounded text features; (b) performs object-level referring for each navigable view with ViLPointer using top-k box features; (c) builds orientation-aware navigable-view representations; and (d) maintains a scene memory storing embedded observations and previous actions, processed by Transformer blocks to yield a memory-augmented state s_a_t for action prediction via attention. At inference, it fuses action logits with scene/object grounding scores (l_t + g_sg + g_og) to reduce search bias and shorten trajectories. Trained with mixed IL+RL losses, this design achieves new state-of-the-art results on REVERIE across seen/unseen splits."}]}
